{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492670"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1125"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1125"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.38,0.02,0.13,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112337"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1125"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94385"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"2147"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13511"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41326"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112337"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman attends the Emergency Department stating that she is concerned about a foreign body she inadvertently swallowed four days ago. She feels well but thinks that by now she should had passed the object in her stools, which she has not. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On physical examination she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The abdominal examination is normal. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Watchful waiting","Ipecac","Polyethylene glycol solution","Endoscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe foreign body is clearly visible (the butterfly-shaped object seen on the top of the X-ray) and is still in the stomach (Image 1). That it has failed to move on after four days suggests that it is stuck in the stomach and efforts will be needed to remove it. An attempt should be made to remove this foreign body \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopically\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not likely to be of any help.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is most unlikely that any emetogenic agents or laxatives (eg \u003Cstrong\u003Epolyethylene glycol solution\u003C/strong\u003E) will help. \u003Cstrong\u003EIpecac\u003C/strong\u003E was once used to induce forceful vomiting in cases of orally ingested poisons, but it has now been replaced by activated charcoal. Polyethylene glycol solution is useful for foreign bodies found further down the digestive tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt should be understood that most foreign bodies that are ingested - either deliberately or accidentally - will make an uneventful trip through the digestive tract. However, the object should be tracked until it is evacuated (\u003Cstrong\u003Ewatchful waiting)\u003C/strong\u003E. If it does not pass spontaneously, then some form of action must be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the foreign body could not be removed endoscopically and a gastrostomy was required. The patient had inadvertently swallowed a decoration from a cake (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most ingested foreign bodies will pass through the gut unhindered."],"references":["Hong KH, Kim YJ, Kim JH, Chun SW, Kim HM, Cho JH. Risk factors for complications associated with upper gastrointestinal foreign bodies. World J Gastroenterol 2015;21:8125-31. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4499356/","Dawes L, Rasuli B, Walizai T, et al. Foreign body. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 29 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1349"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94385"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1125"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15153"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20568"},{"type":"media","id":"20686"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15153"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f1bfb5cc-f852-4e51-a117-457192bfed22.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f1bfb5cc-f852-4e51-a117-457192bfed22.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":482,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20568"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RNZmV8OcIhmKbNKu4AWZ3lp0uqBFlT.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/RNZmV8OcIhmKbNKu4AWZ3lp0uqBFlT.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":482,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20686"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/22AkvEPwSThZ8EJc9FICHyi8druHZI.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/22AkvEPwSThZ8EJc9FICHyi8druHZI.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94385"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T08:45:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T08:45:54+09:30"},"relationships"